    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What is MBTI?</summary>
        <p>MBTI stands for the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator, a personality assessment developed by Katharine Cook Briggs and her daughter Isabel Briggs Myers based on Carl Jung's theory of psychological types. The instrument assigns individuals one of 16 personality types based on four dichotomies: Extraversion vs. Introversion, Sensing vs. Intuition, Thinking vs. Feeling, and Judging vs. Perceiving. It is one of the most widely used personality frameworks in the world for self-discovery, team building, and career exploration. You can <a href="/test/personality-type-test/">take our free 16 Personalities Test</a> to discover your type.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the rarest personality type?</summary>
        <p>INFJ is consistently reported as the rarest MBTI personality type, making up roughly 1 to 3 percent of the general population. INFJs are characterized by deep empathy, strong intuition, and a desire to help others on a meaningful level. ENTJ and INTJ are also among the less common types, particularly among women. However, these percentages vary across different populations and studies, so rarity should not be treated as a measure of specialness or value.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can your MBTI type change?</summary>
        <p>Your core MBTI type is generally considered stable over time, but it is not uncommon for people to test differently on different occasions. This happens because the MBTI measures preferences, not fixed traits, and your preferences can shift with age, experience, stress, and personal growth. Most practitioners believe your innate type remains the same but that you develop greater access to your less-preferred functions as you mature, making you appear more balanced over time.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is MBTI scientifically valid?</summary>
        <p>The scientific validity of the MBTI is debated among psychologists. Critics point out that it has lower test-retest reliability than instruments like the Big Five, that people often get different results when they retake the test, and that the dichotomous categories do not reflect the continuous nature of personality traits. Supporters argue that the MBTI is a useful framework for self-reflection and communication, even if it does not meet the same psychometric standards as research-grade personality measures like the <a href="/test/big-five-personality-test/">Big Five</a>.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How does MBTI differ from the Big Five?</summary>
        <p>The MBTI assigns people to one of 16 categorical types based on four dichotomies, while the Big Five measures five continuous dimensions of personality: Openness, Conscientiousness, Extraversion, Agreeableness, and Neuroticism. The Big Five is considered more scientifically rigorous because it uses spectrums rather than binary categories and has stronger research support. The MBTI is more popular in self-development and workplace settings because its type-based system is easier to understand and apply in practical contexts.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

